<!--EZCODE HTML START-->          <h2>The Exodus Fellowship Story</h2><!--EZCODE HTML END--> <br>
<!--EZCODE HTML START-->          <h4>As told by Kamdar Entil'Zha</h4><!--EZCODE HTML END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HTML START-->          <h3>Introduction:<br>
Of Allies and Enemies…</h3><!--EZCODE HTML END--> <br>
As I write this, we are fast approaching the one year anniversary of our humble Fellowship, and lately I have done a lot of reflecting on the beginnings of our Guild.  I look back fondly on the past year and see that we have grown into a family of friends that really cares about each other and loves adventuring together.<br>
<br>
If you are like me, you have made some good friends in Norrath.  Our guild is proud to call Primal Blood and Circle of Shields our allies, and we are friendly with a number of other guilds.  Hopefully soon we will be adding more to our list of official allies.  But there was a time when our guild was an enemy to another guild.  Not by our decision, but by their leader's.  I personally had a bounty over my head and was to be killed on sight if I was spotted lurking in the lands of what once were my former brothers and sisters (not an easy thing to do on a non PVP server!).<br>
<br>
To understand how this happened is to tell the story of our very creation. And to go back several months before The Exodus Fellowship was born. The origin of our guild cannot be told without telling the story of another guild. A guild that many of our Fellowship’s founders had come from.<br>
<br>
For now, and for future members of The Exodus Fellowship I will attempt to chronicle our story and to tell you of the turbulent times we faced.  Though it was not always that way...<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p><IMG SRC="http://www.exodusfellowship.com/Kamdar4banner.jpg"> </p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub84.ezboard.com/ukamdarentilzha.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kamdar Entilzha</A> at: 8/1/02 10:38:18 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000028><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub84.ezboard.com/ukamdarentilzha.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kamdar Entilzha</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Administrator</span><br>  Posts: 365<br> <font color=#A8A8A8>(7/8/02 7:54 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.exodusfellowship.com/Kam_small2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Exodus Fellowship Story</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE HTML START-->          <h3>Chapter One:<br>
From Whence We Came…</h3><!--EZCODE HTML END--> <br>
It all started for me back in February of 2001 (sorry, I don’t know the Norrath date!). I had been away from Norrath for awhile, and decided to visit it’s lands once again, for what I thought might be the last time. Other worlds had taken up my attention of late and I thought my time in Norrath was coming to a close. As I was wandering the treetop platforms of Kelethin, wondering if I should give away what meager possessions I had, I heard a call ring out from below the platforms. <br>
<br>
The voice was coming from someone named Xellosx and he was calling out for the local citizens to join him in the formation of a new guild. Early on in my life, I had belonged to a group known as The Guardsmen of Norrath. I had liked the sense of family that they had offered. Strangers united in a common cause to help one another, with no expectations. Unfortunately, after several leadership changes their ranks had dwindled until finally they disbanded. Anyway, remembering the sense of family I had with GoN, I thought it might be fun to get in on the very beginning of a new guild.<br>
<br>
I met Xellosx down at the bottom of the lift where several people had already gathered. He was a druid of about the 16th season. Fairly young to be running a guild I thought, but I was only a few seasons above him, and it was the quality of the leader that mattered to me, and not necessarily the years of experience. I asked Xell a few questions about the guild and about himself. He told me that his full name was Xellosx Darketernal and that he and his “brother” Erdrix Darketernal had come from another guild called The Valor of Virtopia, but that guild had grown too big and were no longer a friendly place to be. Now they wanted to start a new group that would always be willing to help each other when in need. <br>
<br>
That seemed reasonable to me. I then asked him if our new guild would have a website, so that when we were not in the world of Norrath, we could still communicate with each other, and it would also serve as a place where visitors could get to know us and what we were all about. He assured me that it would, and that Erdriix, who would be co-leader of the guild, was an “expert” in a strange language known as HTML. Armed with his knowledge he would be able to create such a site. It all sounded pretty good to me, and so I accepted his invitation to join The Eternal Stormcallers. Less than a week later, the powers that be made it official and we were on our way… Xellosx was named Leader, Officer Erdrix was to be considered Co-Leader and would have the official Leadership passed to him when Xell would be away for extended periods. And a Paladin named Gustur was also made an Officer.<br>
<br>
After a week or so, I had asked again about the site, and/or a message board so that we could at least plan events a little more easily. Our members just seemed to be roaming the countryside randomly with no real purpose. I was assured that the site was being worked on and that it would be available soon. It was either because of my enthusiasm or maybe perhaps to shut me up, that I was made an officer of the guild. Proud that I had advanced so quickly and impressed that Xellosx and Erdrix recognized my worthiness I relaxed a bit. I was sure that Erdrix would debut our site any day and it would be something our new and growing group would be proud of.<br>
<br>
Another week had passed and still nothing. I had managed to speak to Erdrix and he admitted to me that he hadn’t yet had the time to work on our site. We hadn’t had any guild events because there was really no way for us to communicate and get organized. I then took it upon myself to create a message board for us. I also informed Xellosx that I might be able to lend a hand in the creation of our website.<br>
<br>
Xellosx’s first message on our new board:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>          <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>          “Hey everyone. Your fearless leader here, just thought I'd leave a little message. Thanks to Kamdar for putting this board together. We have great plans in store for ES, so stay tuned and make sure you stick with us as we go through all these changes. The webpage production is still in it's planning stage, as Kamdar and Reztius are both likely candidates to work on it, with Gustur as Graphical support I believe. I would like to ask that all members, when posting, leave their emails as I plan on sending out guild announcements and updates. Not much else to say, but keep up the great work all of you.”</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
What great work? We hadn’t done anything yet! And as far as our leader being “fearless” I had yet to see him in action, because we did not have our first raid yet! I couldn’t help but notice that Erdrix, the Master of HTML was no longer listed as working on the site. I contacted the others that were mentioned in the post about the website. They gave me their blessing to try to get something up as soon as I could. I wrote to Xell, asking him if he could come up with some opening line for the front of our site. He told me he would get right to work on it. Days passed and again, nothing. And so our website debuted and on the front of it were these words, that I wrote…<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>          A storm has been brewing…All manner of hideous creatures have been marching on the land. A rising flood of Orcs, Goblins, Zombies and Spectres have been encroaching on the once peaceful lands of Norrath. Once thought to be merely legends, the Ancient Sarnak have also returned to wreak havoc upon the unsuspecting and the innocent <br>
Not being able to turn their backs on the coming threat, two brothers known as Xellosx and Erdrix Darketernal formed a fellowship. An alliance made up of many different races, all dedicated to returning the land back to the peaceful inhabitants of Norrath. These brave heroes do not fear the coming evil. They welcome it. For the sooner the threat is met head on…The sooner the storm will be over.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
It was not a literary masterpiece, and it had not even come from our leader, but he approved it, and the site soon went up, with a portrait of Xellosx and Erdrix right on the welcoming page.   It was still missing things like a Charter and a Code of Conduct… but all of our members were listed and it was a place to start. We were still a very small group of less than 20, but we steadily started to grow. Two notable members that would play a part in the future soon joined our guild. Arrwen, a lovely female Ranger (and who just happens to be Arri’s Alternate), and a Druid named Ienoldar.<br>
<br>
And at last, Xellosx announced our first raid….<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>          <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>          “Ok folks, you have all gone on and on about a raid, well here it is folks. Due to many suggestions, i have made Crushbone the first raid we will hold. It will be held On Saturday, March 30'th at 9:00 eastern time. If you miss this, i don't want to hear any complaints. A guild leader has alot to do. I, along with my officers are doing all they can to make ES the greatest guild ever. Also, ALL RAIDS, WILL be posted here.. so make sure you check the board often.<br>
Thats it for now.<br>
Your fearless leader,<br>
Xellosx Darketernal”</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Everyone was expected to attend! Gustur had posted a very impressive strategy for us on the board and we were all looking forward to handing Emperor Crush his own head. At least the 8 of us that showed up for the raid were excited. Our fearless leader was not one of them. After we had waited about 45 minutes for him or Erdrix to show up, we decided to go in without either one of our leaders.  The Raid did not go well.  After several deaths a few took off for other less deadly areas and Gustur, upset by how the raid had gone, handed in his resignation and left the Stormcallers forever.<br>
<br>
That night on the message board a little imp ranger known as Cairpre, who had been one of the few of us that had shown up for the raid left a rather scathing post about the failure of our first raid. He also took delight in pointing out that our leader was not there. Xellosx responded with venom in his voice… “If you must know I had a *%$!ing family emergency!” He ranted on for a little while, mostly lambasting Cairpre, and how it was too bad that Gustur left but it was none of his concern.<br>
<br>
I, however, was concerned. For the first time I really wondered if Xellosx was fit to be a leader...<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub84.ezboard.com/ukamdarentilzha.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kamdar Entilzha</A> at: 7/8/02 8:41:58 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00000F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub84.ezboard.com/ukamdarentilzha.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kamdar Entilzha</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Administrator</span><br>  Posts: 366<br> <font color=#A8A8A8>(7/8/02 7:56 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.exodusfellowship.com/Kam_small2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Exodus Fellowship Story</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE HTML START-->          <h3>Chapter Two:<br>
The Gathering Storm</h3><!--EZCODE HTML END--><br>
Two of the finest friends I have made in Norrath are an Ogre Shaman named Burak, and Wiggam, a Dwarf Paladin.  While of completely different statures, and races for that matter, both are big of heart and honor.  Both were in their 20’s when I came across them and neither had belonged to a guild yet.  Burak had friends in Mensa D'Morte and although Wiggam was far away from their minimum age of 45, he had his eye on The Guardian Lords.  Somehow, I had talked both of them into joining the Stormcallers though it wasn’t easy!   Wiggam took the most time feeling us out.  I knew that when he joined a guild, he was serious… he wanted it to be for good, and he wanted it to be the only guild he would ever join. When I got them on board I was pretty happy.  <br>
<br>
Things were also going well for Arrwen and Ienoldar.  Both had made Officership (at my request) and were becoming fine members of our guild as it continued to grow.  Arrwen’s husband, Sinclair joined us as well as Ien’s wife Angeleena.  <br>
<br>
We had planned another raid on Crushbone and this time Xellosx had shown up.  He invited another “brother” by the name of Varden Darketernal to join us.  This time the raid went quite a bit smoother under the Paladin’s watchful eye.   He was somewhere in his mid 30’s and although he had the power, he did not intrude, but offered aid when it was needed.  He wore the banner of Xellosx’s former guild, The Valor of Virtopia.   After we put the hurt on Emperor Crush and Ambassador D’Vinn, we called the raid over and toasted our success.  As far as I know, that was the last raid that our fearless leader ever attended.<br>
<br>
Xellosx would often disappear for weeks at a time, from both Norrath and the messsage boards.  He would not answer his mail and Erdrix, who I learned was not a real brother, but did know him for several years of adventuring, could not locate him.  During one of the earlier disappearances Erdrix was going to travel the four or five hours to Xell’s house to see what had happened.   Then Xell would show up again and be rather evasive as to his whereabouts.  He would inevitably say now its time to get back to the hard work of running this guild.  <br>
<br>
Let me tell you a little something.  I never saw Xellosx work hard.   After many requests for a Charter and a Code of Conduct, there was still nothing.  I showed Xell a couple of examples from other guilds.  He said, “These are fine!  All we have to do is change a few of the names!”   That wasn’t exactly the way I wanted to do it, but at least it was something.<br>
<br>
One of Xell’s problems was that he would never follow through.  He would say, “Big things are coming!”  but they never did.  He would talk of holding officer meetings, but none were ever scheduled.  All the while he would constantly remind the members how hard he was working for them.<br>
<br>
When he was around the message boards, I couldn’t help noticing that he had a rather condescending attitude toward the members.  He would often snap at people, and more than once I had suggested that he may want to be a little kinder in his posts, that the members should not see their leader become angry. Sometimes he would agree with me and other times he would accuse me of always taking the side of others.  Which I must admit… I often did.  I guess I felt the general membership needed a bigger voice.  Someone that maybe had a little more influence than they did.  This would especially happen with Cairpre, who knew just how to push Xell’s buttons.  Cairpre was a young lad, barely starting adolescence and very immature.  Xellosx was much older, but you would never know it by listening to their conversations.   Cairpre was booted out of the guild on a couple of occasions by Xell, when he would lose his temper.  More than once I came to the aid of Cairpre and spoke on his behalf.  The final time Cairpre had made light of the Darketernal name and that was the last straw for Xell.  Carpre was disbanded and would never be allowed back in again.  He publicly apologized several times to Xell, but to no avail.  Before he disappeared from the halls of the Stormcallers forever, Cairpre had thanked me for the times I stood up for him and gave me a gift.  An Icy Blade that I still carry to this day.<br>
<br>
While Xell continued to do very little work, he had a few requests of me.  First off, I was to get an ICQ account so that we could get instant messages.  Next he created a Hotmail email account that all Officers would use.  We were told the password and from now on we were to use that email for official guild business.  This made little sense to me.  I did not see what was wrong with our separate emails.  In addition, our website already had a chat room.  But even with all of these lines of communication, Xellosx was not an easy man to get a hold of.  Especially when he pulled one of his disappearing acts.<br>
<br>
During one of our instant messaging sessions, I had the following conversation with Xell…<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>     <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>     Xellosx: Just so you know another one of my alts is Zelas, I had guild leadership switched to him.. so I will be on that character for a while now... I have to start him over, so put him as a level 1 Half Elf Warrior.  I plan on leveling him to Xellosx's level in just a few days in Kunark... All that needs to be said is that my main character for right now is Zelas.   Anyways I need to go, get back to you soon... in 15 or so...<br>
<br>
Kamdar: Wait, Xellosx is still the leader, correct?<br>
<br>
Xellosx: Leadership has already been passed to Zelas. which I am going to use from now on. Or for a little while at least, leadership can be passed back and forth to my characters, by the way.<br>
<br>
Kamdar: Our guild leader is gonna be a level 1?   I think for the sake of continuity you should keep it the way it is.<br>
<br>
Xellosx: He will be leveled and ready soon. he has a ton of new equipment as well.<br>
<br>
Kamdar: This is really going to cause havoc with the members not to mention the website, I wish you wouldn't.<br>
<br>
Xellosx: How so? I will let all know that Xellosx = Zelas…  not a big deal..  I plan on playing both characters, Xellosx is an officer and Zelas is now leader... so people will get used to it in no time.  Also,Erdrix will now be playing his warrior, Ragna.<br>
<br>
Kamdar: What about the front page of the website with the pictures and descriptions of you and Erd as leaders…. or the leaders title at the top of the members page?<br>
<br>
Xellosx:  Leave it as it is... its not important, because Xellosx is still to be considered leader, I am only saying I will be playing Zelas a bit.. as long as people know that Zelas=Xellosx then theres no problem.<br>
 <br>
Kamdar: Guess I will need a new picture of the new leaders, I don't really like this but you are the boss....I think it is confusing for continuity sake....Why don't you ask the other officers what they think?<br>
<br>
Xellosx:  No you dont need a new picture man i will put Xellosx back as leader in a week or so.. no one even needs to know.. infact ok Xellosx is still to be considered leader...<br>
<br>
Kamdar: Signing off....Later.<br>
<br>
Xellosx:  Eh, are you mad?<br>
<br>
Kamdar: Nope just a little confused....NP!<br>
<br>
Xellosx:  The picture doesnt need to be changed, nor does the page Xellosx is leader I am just playing a different character for a little while.. nothing has changed I was just informing you of my new character for a little while..<br>
<br>
Kamdar: It will be done on the web page in about an hour  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     <br>
<br>
Xellosx:  lol all you need to do man is add Zelas to my alts section thats it. heh...</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Well, it appeared that I got him to do a complete turn around… Here I was trying to build a history for us and Xell was immediately trying to re-write it!   It was a very small victory…I eventually changed Ragna to the Co-leader and made the front page description a little more generic sounding.  I also replaced the picture of Xell and Erdrix with one of an approaching storm.  As it turned out, that picture would become very prophetic.<br>
