Seeds of Discontent</h3><!--EZCODE HTML END--><br>
Burak and Wiggam were like the Angel and Devil on my shoulders. They were the Ying and the Yang.  That Ogre would always be giving me evil ideas, while Wig tried to be the voice of reason. But all three of us were good friends.  I was hunting with them in The Overthere and the conversation was turning to our options.  <br>
<br>
Burak was filling my head with thoughts of rebellion, “The Ogre in me says that you start a new guild and website. Incorporate the stormcaller tag in the new name like Stormcaller Elite and use the Stormcallers website to point to the new site… That should chap their ass!   <br>
<br>
This sounded very appealing to me.  Oh, what I wouldn’t give to see the look on Xellosx’s face as his guild was slipped out right from underneath him.  He would flip his lid!  Of course Wiggam pointed out that it was not a very honorable way to do things and I should be more up front about it, if I intended to leave.  He also asked me if I wanted to start all over again, after the hard work of building both the website and the guild.  After all, wasn’t I trying to take a breather?<br>
<br>
You see, I had recently stepped down as an Officer.  I had told the others that I did not have enough time to put into the game and I had to focus on other things.  This was partially true.  But it was also true that I did not feel like serving as an officer under Xellosx and the rest of the Darketernals any longer.   I also wanted to see if our leaders would step up to the plate now that my role was diminished.  Maybe they would start leading their own guild. <br>
<br>
I also I felt unappreciated. Xellosx kept me as an Officer, as one Darketernal after another was put in the ranks of Leader.  I felt taken for granted.  He would just send me an email or instant message that would say, “Add the latest Darketernal to the Leaders section!”   They were new to the guild and none of us knew anything about them.  This did not sit well with me.  I told Xell that I would keep up the website as best I could, but I would not be able to be around as much.<br>
<br>
And now, as I stood there on the slopes at the edge of The Overthere, the discussion went on.  Burak and Wiggam essentially said that whatever I decided, they would back me.  I could tell though, that they were both clearly conflicted.  The big guy still had real life friends in Mensa D'Morte that were constantly trying to lure him over.  Wiggam thought that as long as we could just hang out and hunt together, that what went on in the rest of the guild didn’t really matter that much.  I decided not to do anything rash.  Maybe we could give it just a little more time.<br>
<br>
                       _____________________<br>
<br>
<br>
A few days later Arathain announced that he wanted a raid.  Rather than wait for the Leaders to set one up, which they had yet to do, I suggested that he try to get one going himself.   “I would suggest you just go ahead and schedule one, see if people sign up, and maybe you will get a decent turnout. Bungleneck did this and it turned out to be a fairly decent raid. We have had others though with dismal turnouts. It seems to be quite an endeavor to get a large group of us together.”<br>
<br>
Varden joined the discussion, “Well to go on a raid for the sake of raiding is no good.. We need a goal here. Is there something we are after? Need an item? Want to rescue a holy relic of some sort from the vile clutches of Soandso?” <br>
<br>
Probably spurred on by my suggestion, Arathain went ahead and set up the raid.  It was to be a raid on Runnyeye, Sunday, July 1, 2001.   I was glad he set it up and hoped all would go smoothly.  After all, why should he wait for the leaders to set one up?  As far as I could see they were sitting on their hands.  Sadly, this was the first raid that I would be unable to attend, and I hoped all would go well.   Unfortunately he had an extremely low turnout.  <br>
<br>
The next day Arathain posted the following, with the header: “Another Failed Raid Attempt,” <br>
<br>
“Well, so much for that. Only Cobo, Arrwen, Wamphyre, and myself showed. There were other people online at the time, but we were the only ones able to make it, I guess. We decided 4 people didn't constitute much of a raid, so we cancelled.”<br>
<br>
Xellosx responded with “Keep in mind that this raid was not organized nor planned by any of the leaders. Saying &quot;another failed raid attempt&quot; does not apply to this situation. Also, I believe the post by Varden clearly states that having a raid just for the sake of going on a raid isn't such a good idea. Had this been more planned out, it might have been more successful. If anyone has an idea for a raid, feel free to submit one. I think however, that a goal for a raid is needed, instead of having one with no purpose.”<br>
<br>
Tactful, as usual.<br>
<br>
Arathain quickly answered, “The purpose, Xell, was to try and have a guild event, where some of the members could get together and get to know each other better. I would think that this would be an ideal reason for a leader to attend an event. I have kept up with what's going on in the guild, and have posted on many occasions, but have yet to do anything for or get anything out of the guild outside of the message board. And frankly, I would like for the guild to be a little more organized and social. So I tried to help this along. I did not originally plan on organizing the raid, nor did I want to, but when I asked for one, none of the leaders seemed interested in organizing one, and I was told to go ahead and schedule it. I would have thought that the leaders would have tried to support their minions, and maybe help organize (or at least try to attend) any guild function, even if it was &quot;not organized nor planned by any of the leaders&quot;. I mean, I know of 3 leaders that were in Norrath at the time and only Arrwen showed up. But it doesn't matter anyway, because it wasn't planned by the leaders, so it doesn't count, I guess. So I suppose I'll just keep my nose out of things and wait for the &quot;leaders&quot; to do something.”<br>
<br>
Cobo tried to remain calm, “You both have really good points, why dont we just try it again soon?<br>
<br>
Several members also added their input, but to my surprise, it was Varden Darketernal that tried to put things in perspective.  “Lets not get all bent out of shape here, throwing condescending remarks at people will not solve any problems. First of all try to remember we are just a baby guild, and not all of our kinks have been worked out. Secondly it is not the intention of the guild leaders to reign supreme and not let members have minds of their own. Everyone counts here, no exceptions to that rule.”<br>
<br>
Arrwen echoed Varden’s thoughts, “Thank you Varden. Well put.”<br>
<br>
Varden started to seem like a Darketernal that I might be able to deal with.  I wrote to him asking if he could possibly explain the whole Darketernal thing to me, since I was apparently out of the loop.  I also voiced my concerns over Xell’s lack of follow through on anything.  And I asked what had happened to Ragna (formerly Erdrix).  He was still listed as a leader but no one had seen him for several weeks. It had reminded me of Xell’s old disappearing acts.<br>
<br>
Here was his response...<br>
<br>
&quot;The issue of Ragna is that he has been out of the country for awhile, I personally am not sure when he is going to return but Xellosx is more in contact with him.<br>
“Now as far as leaders go, the guild is sponsored by House Darketernal, which is headed by myself. House Darketernal is not just in Everquest but in many many places and has been around for about 5 years and also does not exist only in the cyber realm. Since the guild is sponsored by House Darketernal, all of the family have been given leader status, which means all are of equal standing in this guild. Now as far as who is in charge overall it should not matter. Now as far as leaders are going our.. structure is going to change soon. Instead of just having &quot;leaders&quot; and &quot;officers&quot; we will be having a council of elders which will probably be 1 high level character from every class in our guild. The leaders will stay in place as sort of like uh... being at the top of the pecking order. Which means when people outside of the guild are upset they can yell at us. The leaders will still be on the highest level ! but the decisions will be made by the elders and all elders whether they are leaders.. or officers or whatever will have a say. Also it is good to have more than one leader as it keeps everyone in check including the leaders. <br>
“As far as follow through.. don't worry my friend, but also stay patient. We are trying to do something no one else has done and hopefully it will work, but we need to make sure we got it right before we introduce it to the guild.<br>
“I admit, we need to pick up our room a little here as rearrange the furniture...maybe even remodel the entire damned house but, hey we will get it done.. the more help we have.. the quicker we will get it done.”<br>
<br>
<br>
Well, I was happy he answered me so quickly and openly, but I was also not very pleased to hear that the guild that I helped create was “sponsored” by some previously unknown entity.<br>
<br>
Later that day Xellosx again responded to Arathain’s raid and the discussion that followed, “It was not my intention to be &quot;harsh&quot; with Arathain, although it appears we both were with each other. I apologize, however i would not like to see this happen again, on anyones account.. We're all a family clan, not supposed to be enemies. At any rate, if you want it you wil get it. Now for the GOOD news.....The leaders will plan a raid, just to show that we are not slackers ^_^<br>
We have a rough job just keeping the guild running, but sure we'll take yet another job and supply you all with a great raid. =-)&quot;<br>
<br>
Somehow Xell can come off as apologetic and condescending at the same time.  And he was kindly going to give everyone a raid, even though it might interfere with his busy schedule… Oh Boy!<br>
<br>
Needless to say I was less than impressed.  And I finally decided that it was almost time to make a move.<br>
<br>
                          _____________<br>
<br>
<br>
That night I was back in The Overthere with Wiggam and Burak.  I told them what I intended to do.  Wiggam still thought that I may be acting hasty.  Burak said he was behind me.  But I knew his heart was in another place. I thanked him for his friendship and loyalty, then I told him that he should really go with Mensa D'Morte.  I knew that was where he wanted to be.  He offered me his alternates Nymwasob and Elaam and I gladly accepted their allegiance. <br>
<br>
Now with Wiggam seeing that “The Three” would no longer be in the same guild.  He had his own thinking to do.  Paladins are men of honor.  When he pledged himself to The Eternal Stormcallers, it was not a thing he took lightly.  It was something that he intended to do only once.  Still with far off dreams of The Guardian Lords in his eyes, he promised to go down this road with me… at least for a little bit, to see where it would lead. <br>
<br>
As the night drew to a close we made camp, with the knowledge that things were going to change.  And for what I was planning, I knew that I was going to need more help.  Before I turned in, I shot a letter off to Arrwen.  It was probably the briefest letter I had ever written.<br>
<br>
“One question...” it said, ”Will you follow me if I start a new guild?”<br>
