A Fellowship is Born</h3><!--EZCODE HTML END--><br>
“I can't believe I just found out about this” Wyndlancer, a Druid of the 33rd season exclaimed.  “It's great to know that many more feel the same about ES that I have since I joined, there's no organization and really no activity. I look forward to starting new, and it's great to see many of the names that I would gladly fight to the death in a group with.&quot;<br>
<br>
Wyndlancer was a welcome sight indeed.  Our numbers had been dwindling and I was starting to worry that we may not have enough folks to start the Fellowship of Light as we were calling ourselves at the moment.  Varden had managed to stop many of our co-conspirators from defecting with his announcement of the new ideas he had for the Eternal Stormcallers.  Another one of our recruits, Tomani, had announced that he would be out of town for a month, and would probably be joining us upon his return.  At my last count, that would be six of us that would not be there for our formation.  <br>
<br>
Yet, what was becoming our core group, Arri’s followers would not be swayed.    Back in the forum of the Stormcaller’s, Arathain was the next of us to officially announce his intent to leave.  “I am joining Kamdar, Arrwen, and others in the task of starting a new guild. Good luck, everyone, I'll see you out in the field.”  <br>
<br>
As far as the Stormcaller leadership was concerned things must have started to look dim. Varden spoke up, “As the below posts say many are beginning to leave us. I must say it breaks my heart truly. If there is something I did wrong, or if there is something I did not do at all. I am sorry. If it is the changes I posted about, then I will retract them... give me suggestions on what you want.  I can understand why you who are leaving are doing so. But at the same time, I have heard you speak of friendship and devotion and family. I offer that here and if I have to retract all my suggestions so that we all can plan new ones then I will do just that. I must say also that I have become greatly discouraged but I am not one on giving up. We can do this thing if we want it. I would hear all you have to say and I will work hard with you to make this a great guild. I ask only for the chance to prove myself.” <br>
<br>
Again, I was feeling a little guilty and somewhat sorry for this new leader of the Eternal Stormcallers.  If only he had been there in the beginning, many of us would not have passed the point of no return.  <br>
<br>
He continued, “If I can do anything to change your mind, tell me and I will try with all my power to do it. I ask you please not to give up on us.  As leader I am your servant, what I do I do it for you.  Please, I beg you stay with us, help us, and together we will make this the best guild ever. Do not give up on us.”<br>
<br>
Arathain answered, “Don't take it personally. Some of us are just ready to move on. Your ideas sound good, and I think they will work well. I have a feeling that you will be a good leader, and ES will thrive under your direction. I truly hope so. At any rate, you will lose plenty of people over time, but hopefully you will gain more. Don't take it personally.  Good luck! I think you are headed in the right direction.”<br>
<br>
Then Arathain tried to lighten things up a little, “Maybe sometime our guilds could get together and declare war on the Legion of Little Folk or something.”<br>
<br>
Varden seemed to appreciate Arathain’s attempt. “Ha-ha!” he chuckled, “Legion of little folk! That sounds grand!”<br>
<br>
Although Varden’s mood seemed to lighten somewhat, I felt the need to speak up. “Varden, I believe you to be a noble and honorable Paladin and a good leader. Your ideas sound great and we may even try to incorporate them into our new home. Trust me. It is nothing you have done. And I don't believe there is anything you can do.  The time has just come for some of us to move on.  I hope there are no bad feelings, and I hope we get the chance to share another drink or two.  Perhaps we can even come together for guild events. Hopefully we will be formed by the end of the week.”  Then I attempted my own stab at levity, “So keep your eye out for....Stormcallers: The Special Edition!  Just kidding the real name is going to be...Stormcallers Part Deux!”<br>
<br>
Ienoldar made his position official, as he wished me farewell.  “It hurts to see a brother go.  I wanna thank you for all hard work you have done for us Kam.  Neither that or you shall be forgotten.  I wish you and your new crew all the best, and that your wishes may come true.  Farewell brother.”<br>
<br>
Then finally another Darketernal spoke up.  Surprisingly, in his own way, Xellosx kept it civilized.  “I saw this coming.  i am lead to believe this has been thought of for quite some time. But anyways ...good luck on whatever you guys do. Maybe we can at least form an alliance, and work together eh?  Let me know what you all think. But eh... heh,  I ask to please not use a guild name like ours.  There will only be one band of Stormcallers, and we're it baby.”<br>
<br>
Then Xell even tried to lighten things up in his own way. “Send in your coat sizes, I have some gifts for you, they are nice and red!  Just kidding!  Good luck friends, stay safe, and see you in the field.”<br>
<br>
Trying to keep it light, I came back with, “Is Stormcallers: The Next Generation, different enough?”<br>
<br>
Then referring to his lame “Red Coats” joke I said, “As for those red coats, would they be bloodstained tunics perhaps? You are too kind, sir!”<br>
<br>
He answered back, “No they are not bloodstained tunics!  Ever hear ‘the Redcoats are coming, the Redcoats are coming!?’ That’s what they are heh!” <br>
<br>
His little joke of the “Red Coats” didn’t really make much sense to me.  I knew what he was trying to say, but he had it a little backwards.  After all, the “Red Coats” were the British.  We were the ones claiming our independence!   In the interest of keeping the peace, I decided not to try to correct him on that one.  After all, I had seldom seen Xell so reasonable.  He also expressed his dislike for my latest name suggestion.<br>
<br>
As for what our real name would be, we were still narrowing it down back in the “Eye of the Storm”.  We had to come to an agreement fairly quickly.  We were supposed to meet that night in an EQ created chat room to submit our name and have it approved.  For the moment we had settled on the Fellowship of Light.  It was a combination of two of our current favorites, “Fellowship Exodus” and “Circle of Light”<br>
<br>
Herbdiva was quite fond of Fellowship Exodus.  After all, “Exodus” meant to go forth, and that was certainly what we were doing.  I however didn’t think that “Fellowship Exodus” fell trippingly off the tongue.  But I had to agree that we were indeed a Fellowship.<br>
<br>
But after having slept on it the night before I was really starting to like the word “Exodus”.  <br>
<br>
“I'm still not crazy about the word Fellowship before it” I said. “It just sounds funny to me. What about Mass Exodus?  Or just simply Exodus?”  It was determined that we would make our final decision in the EQ Chat room that night.  <br>
<br>
Fortunately other guild matters had not been so difficult for us to sort out.  We agreed that both Arri and myself would be considered co-leaders.  I would hold the actual title, but with all that Arri had brought to this, she deserved the position as well.  However, according to the folks that run Norrath, there can only be one official Guild Leader.  I guess since I had started this little party, the others were willing for me to be the first to be honored with the official position.  Actually with all of my previous doubts, I was surprised they still looked to me as a leader.  We also decided that all officers would have equal say in the decision making process.  Everything would be determined by a majority vote.  I relied on Arri’s recommendations to get several officers out of her group.  At the time we were going with Arathain, Cobo, Tanluin and Wamphyre.  I also said that I thought Wyndlancer would prove himself worthy.  <br>
<br>
Now it was time to meet in the Chat Room we had created to get our guild approved.  One by one we signed on, hoping that there would be the ten that we needed.  A couple of the troops were unable to make it, though Burak had showed with two of his alts.  And although Ienoldar had pledged himself to the Eternal Stormcallers, he was there as well to help us get our start.  I was most grateful.  <br>
<br>
We had the ten that we needed.  Between us, we decided to go with simply “Exodus” for our name.  Everyone gave their approval and I was whisked away to the guild creation area, where I had to fill out the forms!  I had no idea whether the others were still in the chat area or had been bumped out, but I was now on my own.  <br>
<br>
After I had filled out the form, I hit a little snag.  I was informed that “Exodus” was taken!  It must have been on some other server, because I had done a check on our home of Povar.  Now what was I going to do?  The others were gone and it was up to me come up with the name.  I remembered liking the word “Fellowship”, but hating the way it sounded before the word “Exodus” so I switched them around and submitted “Exodus Fellowship” I then logged off and would have to wait for an approval via e-mail.  I logged off and went to bed.<br>
<br>
The next morning, I checked my mail and to my surprise, we were approved!  The next thing we would need to do is gather ten of us in Norrath, and wait for a GM to come and make us official.  We were starting to get excited that we were seeing the light at the end of the tunnel.  Many of us wished we could do it that night, but thought we had better wait one more day to get as many people informed as possible.<br>
<br>
Now that they were officially committed others went to the Stormcallers’ forum.  They kept their messages short and sweet. <br>
<br>
“I am joining Kamdar as well. Thank you for everything. See you in the field!” Cobo said.  <br>
<br>
Niarki followed with “I am leaving to join Kamdar and others. I hope there are no hard feelings.”<br>
<br>
Apparently, Xell was experiencing some hard feelings as things started to get ugly.  “Ok I can see Kamdar leaving, Maybe a few others. But when I learn that (name withheld) is persuading as many Stormcallers as possible to join this new guild, I have to think to myself,  “How low can (name withheld) possibly go?”  This is the most underhanded, sneaky and downright dirty thing someone can do. To think I was going to form relations with this new guild.  I am far too disgusted to possibly do so.  The last thing I am going to say to (name withheld) is keep this up... and you shall have the rest of the ACTUAL Stormcallers a swords reach away from you.  Ugh, this makes me nauseous... pardon me while I lose my dinner out the window.”<br>
<br>
Well I had no idea who “name withheld” was, but it seemed the days of acting civilized were drawing to a close.  Xellosx had also sent me a rather abrupt ICQ message demanding that I turn over the administrator ship of the forum over to him.  In the past I had always avoided this.  I was afraid that he would cut through and edit the forum to his own liking, deleting posts at his every whim.  I was never anxious to give up one of my true powers I had in the Stormcallers, but now I supposed it would be inevitable.<br>
<br>
Trying to hang on to some mode of decorum, I said, “Xellosx, this whole thing was my idea, if you want to blame someone blame me. Everyone in this guild has free will and is able to make up their own minds. As far as I know, no one was begged, bothered or cajoled (much anyway) into joining us. Let me tell you, though that if this action was not taken many would have left anyway. This is a way to keep a lot of us together.”<br>
<br>
“Let me also tell you that because of your guilds recent announcements of changes many of your members have decided to stay with the Stormcallers. Several of these, are good friends, and I respect their decision.  I wish you would respect ours. I myself was quite torn and had to do much soul-searching. From your latest post though, I can see that I have made the right decision, and it feels as though a great weight has been lifted from my shoulders”.<br>
<br>
I then brought up the issue of the forum, “I got your email and ICQ message requesting turning over admin of this message board. I had already sent an email to Varden telling him that I will transfer administrator ship over to you guys as soon as I can. I think I will wait a few days though, so that everyone that wants to can have their say, without the messages being wiped.”<br>
<br>
Then I couldn’t resist, “As for your little joke about Red Coats, yeah, I got it the first time. I was just trying to turn the other cheek. If you ever want to grow as a leader, I suggest you do the same. Also I believe the Redcoats were the British soldiers that the Colonies were trying to break away from.”  So much for my not correcting him!<br>
<br>
“I harbor no malice torward you Xell, and I truly wish things had turned out differently. I don't know some of the other Darketernals well, but I have recently come to realize that Varden is a good and noble man, and I think he can lead you folks into a bright new future. It will just be without some of us.  I did not mean to hurt anyone's feelings during this and I hope we can all be civil with each other. It has just come time for some of us to move on...to go forth.”<br>
<br>
Arathain joined in, “No recruiting was necessary. Besides, a vast majority of the people leaving all know each other in real life and we made this decision before Kam even said anything, so it would have happened anyway. Good luck - don't foster any hard feelings, it's pointless. I would like our guilds to work together, because it would be much more fun.”<br>
<br>
Then Wamphyre spoke up, and for the first time let the Eternal Stormcallers know who we were about to become. “Hail Exodus Fellowship!  All that wish to leave the clutches of the Darkfraternal do so. We are all capable of making our own decisions so if your grudge lies with any specific it lies with the majority. So I suggest you watch your tongue sir.”<br>
<br>
Xellosx snapped back at the Iksar Shaman, “Watch your own tongue, for if you insult my family again you won't have a tongue to watch, got it?”<br>
<br>
Arri quickly followed with, “He wasn't insulting your family. Only you, Xell. It is thee who should watch thyne tongue.  All we wanted was peace, not your venomous replies and accusations.”<br>
<br>
“Oh give me a break,” Xell said. “Like having my last name twisted into Darkfratneral isn't insulting.  Maybe you need your eyes checked. And another thing I find to be interesting is how you and your little rebel clan seem to think I am harsh and even mean to members.  Haha, it's funny but you guys are even worse. posting all this junk on the board like this. Anyways I am done wasting time with you.  Don’t even bother to post a response I dont even want to read it.  Stay off this board.”<br>
<br>
Then changing his tone, Xell posted again, “There are no hard feelings at all.. my only problem is that i received word from several stormcallers that you and others tried to solicit them into joining you.. those who want to thats fine but dont try and convince others who are happy to stay as Stormcallers. And also, since you are leader of this new guild, do me the favor and keep the badmouthing members mouths quiet.. i dont want any problems to arise between any of us.  Again no hard feelings and good luck.”<br>
<br>
I responded, “Just as I have always encouraged for this message board, our members will always be free to speak their minds, though I prefer it to remain civil. And I am not trying to be mean about this but, I think you really need to work on your sense of humor. Try not to be so thin skinned. We should never take ourselves so seriously that we can't enjoy a laugh at our own expense.  The only soliciting I have ever done was to ask people if they were happy with the guild.  If they replied yes, I dropped the subject. No one's arms have been twisted. However I will go public here now and say, anyone who is not happy with The Eternal Stormcallers will always be welcomed by us.  No arm twisting, no bribes.”  Then jokingly I added, “But, I have shiny new weapons here for anyone that jumps ship!”  I admit I was getting a little feisty, but it had been a long time coming.  Underneath my words, I posted a picture of our new banner.  Having decided our name the night before, I had whipped it up rather quickly and was anxious for it to be seen.<br>
<br>
Needless to say, Xellosx was not pleased. “Revolting!  Just when I thought it couldn’t get any worse I see your rebel clan's banner on our site.  Gee, thats a nice touch, and how grown up of you to do so.” <br>
<br>
“No harm was meant, Xellosx” I said.  “You really need to relax. You are making this much more difficult than it needs to be. Flying off the handle is only causing you to look bad in front of your members. You, yourself run the risk of becoming our best recruiter.”<br>
<br>
In my own defense I added, “No malice was meant by me putting our banner up. Truthfully I thought you would have been relieved that we are not called Stormkillers, Son of the Stormcallers, or anything else with the word storm in it. We really wanted to leave without causing much trouble. Believe me if I wanted to I could have slapped our banner on the top of this Message board and have the Eternal Stormcaller website call up our new site instead of the Stormcallers. I have not done this, nor do I intend to.  I have told Varden that I will keep the website up for a month. He can email me articles for the news section if he wants and I will get them up as soon as I can. This should give you folks a little time to regroup and get a new page up. You are also welcome to any graphics, logos etc that you want to take from the current site.  Please Xell, for the sake of your guild, take a breath and calm down. It will all be over soon.”<br>
<br>
“Oh for Tunare’s sake!” Xell exclaimed.  “Your best recruiter? No I think not.  See the Stormcallers back me on this.  I am not the one who needs to take a breath and calm down. I have been calm throughout this.  I am just frankly upset by the way this is going.  Tired of the insults and the like.  I should post the harassing emails I have been receiving and see what results are given.  I agree on one thing,  it WILL be all over soon.  For the well being of the rest of us here at ES I hope.   Kam, you need to stop over reacting and trying to make things bigger then what they really are.  The only people who agree with you is your little rebel clan.  I have discussed this with many ES members and they are saying the same things I have.   Your efforts to shame me or us are not working.  Although I gather it is more so directed at me. Heh, even when you were ES, you have done the same thing, and it has worn on me rather thin.  I, along with the Stormcallers will continue to concentrate on us and not you or the little rebel clan.  So I ask that lets just leave it at this.  The last post about this incident... no more posts on it.. no more anything.. do your things, we will do ours...alright?  Sheesh... it's a good thing I set up a new message board.”<br>
<br>
Two minutes later he posted a follow-up.  “Ahem.  I do wish to say thank you for the allotted time given to keep the site up. It is appreciated.”<br>
<br>
I seriously doubted he was receiving any emails.  I had a feeling that he might be slipping a little more from reality.  I answered back as calmly as I could.  “I am disheartened to hear that you have been receiving harassing emails. I do not know where they are coming from, but I would urge this practice to stop.”  <br>
<br>
Having been watching all of this, Varden decided it was time to step back in.  “Well this is certainly come to arms length fighting. Despite what either party says you guys are baring your teeth and they are stained pink with blood of your previous victims.  I must say I have seen some bad things happen here. I have seen friends at each others throats.  No matter how delicate or innocent you make it sound, you guys are fighting it out.  There is obviously some bad blood here and it needs to be worked out.<br>
<br>
“Xellosx, I will not point out anything to you here where everyone can see but Kamdar speaks the truth. You would do well to take his council on many things, including how to be a leader. Kamdar, you are just and noble but you seem to still harbor some bad blood. Both parties are very quick to point out each other’s flaws, but very reluctant to point out their own.  As I see it both sides are right and wrong. I should not even have to explain, because deep down both parties should already know, but you are human so you deny it to yourself and see yourself as right only. <br>
<br>
Varden continued, “As far as true Stormcallers go.... I fear I am not one of them. I am Virtopian.  Even though my people turned their back on me many times,  that is what I am. It is there that I learned to be who I am.  Since coming here I have met friends, enjoyed playing the game, felt wanted, even needed. Those are perhaps the greatest feelings a person can ever have. But now, I see disunion, avarice, name calling, and revenge.  I even heard my family name,  the name I created to symbolise something be insulted. Well what is in a name anyway? Call me what you will.  But in the end, what will you have?  Maybe you would have won, but at what cost?<br>
<br>
“Who knows?  All I know is that I came only wanting to be a part of something special. Now I am made to fix something.  To pick up a mess.  And now I see friends fighting.  Perhaps I was lonely and ignored in Valor of Virtopia but never was I subjected to such a strife as this.  In all honesty and sincerity, take a look at yourselves and see what you have done. Forget about being right or wrong and take a good look.  Yes it is only a game, but we are still people.<br>
<br>
“Know now that he who was made your leader is now thinking of leaving the Stormcallers. I have seen very little good come from this and I believe both sides need to take a real close look at themselves.  I am reminded of one of my favorite quotes: ‘A friend is someone who knows everything about you and likes you anyway!’  Friends do not do the things I am seeing here. A friend is someone who makes you a better person.  Because of them you are better. Someone like that deserves every benefit of the doubt possible.  Who cares if you are right when it costs you a friend?   At any rate.. I chose no side in this matter. Both of you are no less wrong than the other.<br>
<br>
“Kamdar as I said you a truly a noble man, but you lack tact, perhaps Xellosx needs a better sense of humor but, to point that out will only create more hatred.  Also Xellosx may be flying off the handle about this, but I can not blame him. He is seeing something he created fall apart.  How would you feel about that? I might just feel the same way he does.”<br>
<br>
Varden’s words were stinging a bit.  Actually I was watching something I helped create fall apart too.   Things had managed to get out of control rather quickly in the forum, and I was starting to feel somewhat ashamed.<br>
<br>
Varden went on, “Xellosx, you need to listen well to people. From what I know Kamdar has literally beat down your door to move on things in this guild. You must take the role of leader. You also need to have more patience. I taught you long ago about controlling your emotions. Kamdar has done a great deal for this guild and in my honest opinion if you wanted help with running the guild, you should have looked to Kamdar and not me. I would follow Kamdar, think about that.”<br>
<br>
I responded, “Gulp! Well, I'm almost speechless. Thank you for your words Varden, both critical and complimentary. I will take them to heart. The only thing I can say is that I truly hope that we can someday put this bad blood behind us and come together as allies. They say time heals all wounds...  I hope it is not just a saying.”<br>
<br>
I also wrote a letter to both Xellosx and Varden apologizing for allowing things to get so out of hand.  I told them both that I had nothing to do with any harrassing emails and that I posted to my own people that no such activity was to be tolerated.  I expressed a hope that we could all come away from this without any more hurt feelings.  Xell and Varden seemed to both agree.<br>
<br>
Xellosx posted next…<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>     “After hearing that post.... I am uncertain as what to do.  My first instinct is to continue the fight for what I started so long ago. After also reading that my good friend, and brother for over five years is uncertain as to staying, it sways me.. almost to giving up. But, I will not do so.  Even if I am the ONLY ONE IN THE GUILD LEFT, I will not give up.  I will fight for my beliefs and for all those here at the Stormcallers now. So you know... the dispute that has been at our throats has ended.  We have come to a peacefull solution, and even to regaining our friendship.  Still, I know that a lot of people did not like the posts we have posted.. but I apologize for it..and I am sure the others do too. I am curious, who here will stand by my side and fight for the Stormcallers... fight for the Stormcallers to remain Eternal!<br>
<br>
Who here will do so? Anyone that will .. show your support and post your thoughts at this time.  I could certainly use to see that i am not alone...and that I have brothers and sisters out there in arms... and friendship, who will fight their hardest for us...and not give up.<br>
<br>
I am still pained by what took place... and I realize my share of the mistakes...and humbly ask that everyone forgive me, if it is in their hearts to do so...I only pray....that we survive to tell these stories and remember them,, never to forget...and build from them, learn from them... and grow stronger from them. I know I have. My friends, please stand by my side and fight....fight for a worthwhile cause...fight for the Stormcallers and all we represent...it is needed now more then ever.<br>
<br>
Xellosx<br>
Grief Struck Soldier of the Eternal Stormcallers<br>
Friend to the Exodus Fellowship”</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Several folks then answered Xell’s plea.  Pledging themselves to both him and the Eternal Stormcallers.  It appeared the damage control was finally starting to work for them.<br>
<br>
Back in our own “Eye of the Storm” forum Cobo also agreed that we should let things with the Stormcallers settle a bit.  “Look, I love a good war but now I think we have all stated our opinions and should let the heat die a bit, ignore him is my advice. Then we can kill them all in a surprise attack! Just kidding (sorta) Anyway, Kamdar is the man! I am impressed with Kamdar and Wamp! (He is so pissed!) Arri rocks too! Hope we have enough &quot;little rebels&quot; there tonight!”<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
A few hours later our big moment was fast approaching.  We were gathering in the tunnel in the East Commonlands, awaiting a Guild Master to grant us our guild status.  We were becoming somewhat anxious as there were not the required ten of us present.  Something had come up in the real lives of several of the others, and we were unsure if there would even be ten of us when the GM arrived.  Arri had gone out into the Northern Desert of Ro to see if she could round up one or two more.  <br>
<br>
She came back with a Dark-Elf Rogue named Danmann, and a Barbarian Warrior named Torakon.<br>
<br>
Burak’s alts Elaam and Nymwasob had shown up soon after.  Cobo, Niarki, Tanluin, Chonn, Herbdiva and Wyndlancer were also present.  <br>
<br>
To my utter surprise Wiggam had come running up through the tunnel and greeted us.  He said he had come to wish us well.  I had the feeling that he would have laid his axe next to our swords if we were low on recruits, but by my count we now had twelve.  And so Wiggam the Paladin Dwarf of the Eternal Stormcallers stayed to bear witness to the birth of a new guild.  <br>
<br>
Anticipation was mounting as we were waiting, but the butterflies that had been fluttering in my stomach were gone.  This was going to happen.  <br>
<br>
Soon a dark-haired man dressed in black entered our circle.  He introduced himself as Teliesin Lifebringer and asked who was to be our leader?  Several folks shouted out “Kam!” and with my heart filling with pride I walked up to Teliesin and bowed before him.  <br>
<br>
“I am to be the one,” I said, barely being able to contain the excitement in my voice.<br>
<br>
Teliesin waved his arms, and as if by magic the banner of the Exodus Fellowship appeared above my head.  Cheers rang up from the others and steins were raised in triumph.  Teliesin bid us good luck and farewell and I soon went to my first duty of inviting the others into the guild.  Arri, Cobo, Tanluin and Wyndlancer were promoted to officership.  I would have to catch up with Arathain and Wamphyre later.  <br>
<br>
It was a good time!  As the night wore on toasts were made and Ales were shared.  Sometime later after the effects of the alcohol had dissipated several of us decided that we should head to the Lavastorm Mountains, so that the ememies of Norrath could feel the wrath of our new Fellowship.  <br>
<br>
It had been quite a storm that we had weathered and we had not seen the last remnants of it.  But now a new day had dawned. We were both figuratively and literally moving forth and heading toward that light at the end of the tunnel. As we slowly emerged from the cave, we could see that the dark clouds had parted and the Norrath sun shown brightly on our shoulders.<br>
<br>
It felt damn good.<br>
